nmental, and historical data, Jacka presents a multilayered examination of the impacts large-scale commercial gold mining in the region has had on ecology and social relations. Despite the deadly interclan violence and widespread pollution brought on by mining, the uneven distribution of its financial benefits has led many Porgerans to call for further development. This desire for increased mining, Jacka points out, counters popular portrayals of indigenous people as innate conservationists who defend the environment from international neoliberal development. Jacka's examination of the ways Porgerans search for common ground between capitalist and indigenous ways of knowing and being points to the complexity and interconnectedness of land, indigenous knowledge, and the global economy in Porgera and beyond.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aEthnologyxPapua New GuineaxPorgera. 0aEthnologyzPapua New GuineaxPorgera. 0aEthnologyzPapua New GuineazPorgera. 0aGold mines and miningxEnvironmental aspectsxPapua New GuineaxPorgera. 0aGold mines and miningxEnvironmental aspectszPapua New GuineazPorgera. 0aGold mines and miningxSocial aspectsxPapua New GuineaxPorgera. 0aGold mines and miningxSocial aspectszPapua New GuineazPorgera. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311071182040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822375012zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822375012423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822375012.jpg  a978-3-11-071182-0  DUK eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles